This was a good idea. The activity was practice problems. The activity works well for any subject. 2 truths and a lie was a great closer. I learned a lot from that.
column3: The SI leader was very kind towards students and started the session with a fun fact which was nice to see. The student did seem quite comfortable. The SI leader also asked the student to come up to the whiteboard which fostered a productive learning environment.
column4: I believe it would have been very useful after helping the student solve a problem to have explain their solution from the start and thoroughly. Almost like a presentation. For longer questions, sometimes the students forget how they got to where they are.
column5: I like the SI leader sometimes told the student to take a step back. This can be very useful if a student falls down a rabbit hole. I should do this more. It can be good to quickly correct a student if they're doing something wrong. This also saves time. This type of guidance is really helpful, your almost organizing your students thought process and catching them when it goes in the wrong direction.
column6: I really liked the format you had for your session. You went through some brisk review for a minute or two where you did most of the talking. Then you had the student do a practice problem where you assisted them a lot. And then you sent them off on their own to do a problem and only ask for help when needed. This works well.. You are also a master of the content, its clear you understand it well. One thing that could improve is having the student explain their work or the solution more often. Or at least at the end. If there's a long, complicated problem that I'm helping a student solve, I like to ask them to explain the entire thing to me from the start. I judge a student's understanding of a topic based on how well they can present it. I find that to be very useful and it is something that would fit perfectly into your session. Another tip that might be useful is instead of telling them what they did wrong just circle it or allude to it. Sometimes that works wonder for their understanding of the topic.

column2: The opener could have been more interactive, but it was a brain teaser, so we were pretty stumped. The activities that were content-based were good and allowed the student to show his skills. Closer was good and fun.
column3: They made jokes with them and really allowed it to be peer-led. It also made sure they knew they can use their notes.
column4: Explaining the actual content. There was something he could have done differently or explained it in a way to make more sense.
column5: Interacting with the students and maintaining focus on the topic, without straying from the content. He did well on getting both students to participate in the activities.
column6: Just explain things a little more. Be a little clearer on what you want them to do.

column2: For the opener, SIL asked the students about what they want more practice on, which got the students talking. This is a good way to get feedback from the students and identify knowledge gaps. The main activities consisted of many calculus problems, finding local minima and maxima and approximating the graph of a function. The closer was super fun, guessing football players from a picture.
column3: The students were very comfortable throughout the session. During problem solving, one person was always writing on the board, and the others were there to help if needed. SIL redirected questions, making sure that everyone was engaged. Wait time was also used, as a way to give students the time to think, without giving away the answer.
column4: After finding the x values where the graphs were not defined, SIL could have demonstrated using a graph, that the slope is vertical at these point. This would help build intuition for the students.
column5: SIL had the students research the mean value theorem and rolles theorem and explain it by sketching a graph and showing it to the other team.
column6: He could have prepared something more collaborative for the main activity. While one student was on the board, the others were sometimes side tracked or on their phones.

column2: Very chill opener! They played a wikipedia game in small groups. Class content braindump, Isaac asked them to the recall what they did in class and he would write down when they said on the board making a small concept map/flow chart. The braindump into a discussion on the material was done very well as it built off of the knowledge the students were lacking. Great use of the smaller white boards! The room was set up very well fro a group discussion.
column3: The students and the seemed to be very comfortable working together and collaborating on activities! Isaac actively included everybody in the activities even those more reserved. Isaac congratulated them on their correct answers and redirected questions to the rest of the students when they needed a little help!
column4: Maybe let the students use the markers more instead of writing all of the students ideas yourself. Also, just be more careful with the time you have for each session and make sure you don't go over! Aside from this everything else was very well done!
column5: Isaac did a great job with his redirecting questions and giving the students enough time to think about their answer before answering (Wait time). You did a very good job on calling on the students that weren't as openly participating to make sure everyone participates in the activity. I like the way you used variations of the questions to started with to check the students understanding for specific scenarios!
column6: Great session overall! I love your use of the group discussion strategy to get everyone participating! You had great wait time and redirecting question to other students. You created a great environment for the students to learn and comfortably share their ideas! I liked your way of checking for understanding by asking the groups questions about different problem scenarios. The only things I would try to improve are letting your students lead te session a little more by giving them the marker and and being more mindful of the clock! Great job!

column2:
Opener - I love spotle! Such a great opener to get the students to think, and it also got me a little involved as well lol. I will definitely steal this for one of my sessions.

Activities  - List comprehension: I don't know much about comp sci, but I liked that he got the students up and working on the whiteboard
  Kahoot: great way to test their knowledge and ensure they understand the topics covered!
Practice questions: backup activity in case the other activities were to go faster. Great way to reassess their knowledge! I liked that he had it ready to go rather than scrambling for another activity to do before the closer.

Closer - They ran out of time for the closer, but they had great practice of the content and conversations about the class!
column3: Very welcoming with his students! Before the session even started, he got the students to talk about their classes, the exam they had, which sparked up conversations between him and the students. The students aren't afraid to ask questions, and when a question is asked, he uses his redirecting skills before answering the question himself. He also made sure the students understood the topics covered by asking further questions and playing games to test their knowledge.
column4: It was a great session! Not really much to say otherwise :p
column5: Great activities and a great job redirecting questions and assessing their knowledge! Also, I like that he had extra activities planned in case the other ones went faster than expected.
column6: n/a :)

column2: I like how the SIL was able to immediately gauge the level of understanding from the opener and keep it in mind when continuing with the other activities. I also liked how during the activities he kept asking questions to provoke thought and would redirect questions when appropriate. He managed a balance of having the students work by themselves and work together. He did this by having them take turns or describe the code written by another student.
column3: The SI Leader started off the session with a writing down things you know, which helps allow him and the students to feel the environment of learning. He continuously upkept this environment by asking questions and giving students a launching point for the activities by writing a few lines of code or defining the goal of a function
column4: I felt the SI Leader was a bit more lecturing than student led collaboration, however It was clear on some of the topics the students did not know the topic very well if at all, so It worked in the end.
column5: The SIL did a great job at helping the students feel more confident by redirecting questions and ask questions to the students when necessary
column6: Amazing Session, I could really tell how helpful you are to the students. The agenda on the board gave clear and distinct information about what the session is going to entail. I also enjoyed how the students got involved and your questions to them seemed to be exactly what they needed to give the full answer, but without your question giving any information. The opener was a great way to gauge the level of understanding of the students!

column2: I think the activities were a bit same-y, being just "answer what this code does" in the same format. Understandably it was more of a review session, but I think it might be more interesting to have different ways to check for the students' understanding. Though if that's what the students like, then that's fine.
column3: There was only one student so it's a bit hard to comment on how he would conduct a group session, but I like that he's able to form a connection with the student and chat with them right before the session and then moving into the classroom with them. He seemed to match with the student's mood and personality well.
column4: He could consider coming up with activities that are more collaborative in nature, so anything that requires there to be at least 2 people working together.
column5: I think he did well with checking for understanding, which seems to be the main theme of the session. The activities were definitely meant to probe for their understanding, and he was also often asking student small chunks of questions.
column6: N/A

column2: Steven’s opener was really engaging. By asking about the exam that happened today, he built an immediate connection with the students and made a welcoming tone for the session. The activities were very nice in my opinion as tthe students were really engaged and weren’t afraid to ask questions. The closer was a great way to wrap things up and check in on where the students are after the session.
column3: Great use of wait-time by Steven, he dropped hints to guide students toward the answer when clearly the students are getting no where. He also drew visual python lists that directly related to the topics students struggled with on the exam, and he used gentle redirection to get participation from everyone.
column4: This is a small nitpick, but I would recommend writing the agenda on the board just in case some students arriving late know what’s happening.
column5: Steven did an really good job adapting to what the students needed in the moment. His use of visuals, guiding questions, and wait time show he was really paying attention to where students were getting stuck and adjusting his approach to support them.
column6: Very nice session overall. You created a supportive learning environment, kept students engaged, and responded thoughtfully to their questions. Your sessions are clearly helping students feel more confident with the material.

column2:
Opener: Derivative Rules practice
Good to drill these. I wonder if it's worth the time though if the students are confident with this. Have you seen your students improve their recall over the semester doing this repeatedly? 

Activity: Concept Map
Write conditions for two theorems
Didn't always catch student's mistakes or was confusing e.g. allowing 'f(x) is continuous on (-inf, inf) therefore...' while MVT does not need continuity on (-inf, inf) 
Good guided questions, Rolle's theorem difference to MVT
Asking students to refer to notes is good 
I feel like you could have had the student do more work like when explaining using graphs

Activity: Continuity Review
Good connection to this material. Students def need review of this unit during MVT study.
Letting students work through their thought process is good 
Allowed students to cross-check answers and helped after they didn't catch mistakes
I think you could allow students to draw graphs/etc. 
Time sensitively moves on that's good

Activity: Practice Problems
Allowed students to work out solutions on their own 
Pretty good collaboration between your students
column3:
Casual interaction & small talk throughout the start 
Asking about confidence in the class/struggles is always helpful to make students feel comfortable
Students comfortable joking around
column4: Allowing students to work through their thinking on more theoretical parts like theorems or conclusions (where c goes, what cot is, unit circle)
column5: Fostering collaboration between students and allowing them to think during work and also managing activities/timing was great
column6: Super good work! Great session

column2:
The opener was "birds" and she had her 2 students draw on the board. The students seemed like they were having fun for they were giggling the whole time.

For the main activity, I like how she asked her students whether they want to practice graphs or equations. That way she hits the areas that the students need the most. She was prepared for both. I think she did a great job of having students think through the problems, instead of just giving them answers.

Sydney ended with wordle. It's a fun New York Times Puzzle game and it was a great way to destress after the sessions.
column3: Sydney started the session by simply asking her students how their day went. I thought this was a great way to bond with her students. She was very attentive throughout the activities, she stood right next to her students. She was always available but she never did the work for them.
column4: N/A
column5: She asked great guided questions, to get students to explain their reasoning for the steps that they took.
column6: Great Job!

column2:
Opener - Good review, got the student involved in review in a gamified way

Activities - Rapid-fire multiple-choice questions were great to review conceptual material followed by whiteboard code to solidify practical knowledge. I think this was an excellent template to follow and transitions smoothly

Closer - Left time at the end for personal questions as well as a checking for understanding section
column3: The SI leader redirected questions excellently and tried their best to make the student feel comfortable tackling concepts they didn't understand very well.
column4: Wait time could be expanded upon, like letting the student try to figure out the answer before simplifying or giving it to them
column5:
Writing an agenda is a very practical as well as whiteboard coding to make sure the student understands the code on a conceptual level instead of just practically. 

The leader also left ample time to review any topics the students might have to make for a more tailored session.
column6:
It's tricky dealing with students who might not know certain concepts and at times you might want to just give an answer so you can move on with your session. I'd suggest maybe trying to simplify certain questions or giving examples they might be familiar with to try and nudge them in the right direction. 

Overall, the session was great and I think leaving enough time at the end was a phenomenal move as it's something I struggle with myself.

column2:
No opener or closer for this session.
Love triangle - a math problem centered around a love triangle involving planes. Some planes only like other kinds of planes and the students had to calculate if there were any love triangles in the group. 4 students came up to the board and were doing a nice job writing individually but also helping each other. 2 other students stayed in their seats. This took about 30 minutes so I'm not sure there was an opener.
Kahoot - (3 students left before this) There was a long pause before starting this activity and I was a little confused about what was going on or if the session was over. There were definitely some missed opportunities to redirect questions and check for understanding.
column3: Chris did a great job working with students and encouraging them while they were working. They clearly like him and everyone was joking around. Definitely a positive and fun, yet productive environment.
column4: No agenda on the board- I walked in 1 minute late and didn't know what was going to happen. Also making the two students who were just sitting participate more. It seems like they knew the material, but they should be participating more actively if they're attending SI.
column5: Chris had a good balance of having students figure things out independently and knowing when to step in and redirect them.
column6: I think Chris could benefit from being a little more assertive and organized in session. Students seemed to sort of just be doing what they wanted. The session seemed somewhat helpful for students but I didn't see much of the SI model being used.

column2: The opener (Guess the Movie) was strong but definitely made for a larger group. The first activity (Create a Map) was really good at incorporating the content of using graphs to find concavity and the students had little to no difficulty understanding how to do the activity. The second activity (Find Your Treasure) allowed Jhoelle to take time to clear up concerns that another student had while the other was able to work at a somewhat faster pace.
column3: Jhoelle has a great relationship with her students, making it easy for them to start engaging in conversation and ready to dive into the activities. Some of the student's conversations might create distractions from the content, but Jhoelle does an awesome job redirecting the students back to the activities.
column4: Potentially consider letting the students use their notes when using specific terms (points of inflection, critical points, concave up/down, etc). This would make sure they are demonstrating the material correctly or able to fill in any definitions they might gain during the session. Also don't worry about not getting to another activity if the students seem to be struggling on the current one!
column5: Jhoelle did a great job keeping the student's engaged and focused on the material. If a student had a question, she did a really great job of utilizing it to check for understanding and have another student answer the question. I also liked the range of activities and that there seemed to be no wait/set up time taking away from the session.
column6: Don't be afraid to not get to an activity if the students want to focus/have questions on the one you are currently working on (essentially don't rush). You can always reuse an unused activity in a following session!

column2: No opener but wrote activities on boards. activities were very collaborative and involved all students.
column3: Yes he has a very good relationship with students they were able to stay on task and be productive
column4: Possibly having an opener to segue into math topics. Also when they were going in the wrong direction he took a but long to say something so maybe saying something or asking a question to help them realize their mistake.
column5: Good at redirecting questions and asking for explanations on the steps they took to solve the problem
column6: Overall, very good session!

column2: I thought the opener was a fine opener, it got the people engaged and talking with each other. I think the activates were good, with a good mixture between busy-work for the students to collaborate together, doing individual work for the students, and facilitation from the SI leader. It was a mixture of sheet-handouts, board work, and a sort-of slides gameshow. The closer worked well in ensuring the session was closed and still gave students ample time to work with the SI leader.
column3: They were actively engaged with the students, handed out material, ensured that all students were included and encouraged people to talk with one another, and gave plently of time for questions and help.
column4: I think there may be better opportunities for redirecting questions when going over the answers to material.
column5: I think they did really nicely in ensuring the students had everything they needed related to the activities and had excellent report with making a comfortable environment.
column6: I think it was a really good SI session, it's obvious that the students had a good time and were comfortable and included. It also seemed they had a good rapport with you, and I think had a fantastic time with a positive impact.

column2: I like the opener, infinite craft is always fun. For the activities, the students collaborated well. I like that the SI leader had the students explain their work, this was a good check for understanding. I love having the students come up with companies and then debate which category they're in - it was great for collaboration and also applying what they've learned to real world scenarios. The closer was fun, too
column3: The SI leader was personable and created a fun environment which made the students comfortable and able to to collaborate well.
column4: I can't think of anything to improve, I think the SI leader did a overall great job.
column5: Great redirecting questions. Great checking for understanding of the other student when one of the students gave the answer.
column6: The SI leader did a really great job of getting the students to collaborate, especially in the sorting the companies activity, which got the students debating, strengthening their understanding. I think it would seem hard to make interactive activities for a class like econ, but the SI leader did a great job with this.

column2: The opener was very frustratingly fun. I was losing my mind slightly but I was able to solve the Pips game with SIL. The activities seem like they would have been good for the students. Sophia was able to walk me through process scheduling activity where I had no prior knowledge. The closer would have been rose bud thorn which would have been great for Sophia to gauge where her students knowledge.
column3: SIL fostered a comfortable learning environment by bring in Irin who came earlier for her session to try and participate in the closer. Sophia was good at allowing me and Irin to attempt the Pip on our own without much input from her. I believe she would have does this effectively if she did have students show up.
column4: I believe the SI Leader could improve on her attendance. I understand that she just had an exam and it is snowing, but she did say she typically only has one regular. I believe is she used an incentive, maybe candy, to try and motivate the regular to bring a friend that may help her attendance.
column5: The SI Leader did a good job at redirecting questions, Irin (who is taking the course SIL supports currently) came earlier for her SI session was able to understand the material more than me. Sophia did a good job asking questions to learn what Irin knows as they have different professors. Sophia also did a good job at teaching me from scratch. Sophia is a great teacher even if the students have little to no knowledge about the subject.
column6: The general feedback I have is to not discouraged with having a no show. I have had many no shows in the past. The key is to keep trying and talking with students to find out how to plan sessions around their needs. I have tailored my openers and closers to the interest of my students and that may be something to consider if you have not done so already. You are a great teacher SIL!

column2: I thought the activities were interesting and informative
column3: I thought the atmosphere was generally low stress
column4: I feel like we could have used a little more help on syntax stuff
column5: Generally used the facilitation methods very effectively
column6: Nothing I didn't share in person. Great job!

column2:
Opener - The opener was a fun and interactive activity which served as a good warm-up going into the session. The opener also encouraged discussion among the SI leader and student

Activities - The first activity was a good and relatable premise, which was fun and creative, incorporating the class topics into the activity. The SI leader discussed the activity’s problems with the student well, helping them to find the answer without giving the full answer directly. In addition to giving explanations of the concepts to the student, the SI leader used some simple example problems to help the student understand the basics of the question. After the activity, the SI leader gave a quick summary of what areas the student can improve upon based on the problem. The second activity was a bit shorter due to time constraints. This activity did a good job of building on concepts introduced in the first activity. While shorter, this second activity still felt like a good way for the student to study some of the course content. 

Closer - The closer was another online game, which was a fun way to end the session, keeping the student engaged, while winding down from the more intense academic portion of the session.
column3: The environment felt casual and friendly, while still being one focused on learning. The SI leader would discuss questions with the student openly, rather than relecturing or speaking over them. The SI leader would also give the student adequate time to solve the problem on their own, giving feedback and observations about the student’s work as needed.
column4: The SI leader gave some longer verbal explanations of concepts which could be improved by adding a visual aid, such as drawing on the whiteboard. For instance, when discussing the second derivative test, the concept was a bit hard to visualize without an aid, due to the topic's heavy use of graphing concepts.
column5: The SI leader had a good back-and-forth with the student, keeping up the energy throughout the session. The SI leader was able to have a good conversation with the student regarding the session topics, and it was clear that the student was engaged throughout the session. The SI leader also knew how to give answers and explanations that the student would understand, which was great for tailoring the session to the student’s needs
column6: The session seemed fairly fun and engaging, and the activities were all good at incorporating course content. The SI leader did a good job at managing their time, so that the majority of activities could be completed within the session time. The SI leader had a good rapport with the student, giving the session a welcoming and friendly atmosphere. Overall, the SI leader did a good job of being prepared for the session, with fun activities and relevant content. One area of improvement could be on incorporating visual aids into longer explanations of topics. An area of strength the SI leader demonstrated was a cultivation of a good learning environment. The student was clearly comfortable with the SI leader and was also engaged in learning the course materials.

column2: Even though the session ended up being a no-show, I thought the overall session plan was thoughtful and creative. The opener using Pokémon Showdown was engaging and connected well to real world applications of classes and methods. The planned activities of sorting traits/actions/names into classes, spotting errors in code, and reviewing commonly missed midterm questions were all nice activities in my opinion. The activities really good at checking for understanding and had the students work together. The closer was simple, but I really liked that he asked students for feedback on the previous exam prep so he can improve the next one.
column3: Because there were no students present, there was no interaction this session. However, with Zifeng's explanation of his session plan, I could tell he would interact with the students in a very friendly and welcoming way. He used partner work, group discussion, and hands-on activities, which shows that he intended to create an inclusive and peer-supported session.
column4: I think one thing the SI Leader could work on improving is to improve marketing strategies to get more students to the sessions. I see that he tried to use the java tokens to get more students, but there was still a no show. I think maybe he could write the times and dates of the sessions on the whiteboard if he isn't already doing so or try to have the instructor help market the sessions.
column5: Zifeng created a highly engaging session plan. The activities were interactive, aligned with course content, and it also encouraged students to think about classes, methods, and common errors. I think he made a really engaging session plan and the activities.
column6: Your session plan is creative, thoughtful, and designed with student learning in mind. Even though no one attended today, the session plan showed that you prepared and an understanding of collaborative SI techniques. Keep developing interactive activities like these (especially Pokémon showdown). You should also consider strategies to increase attendance so more students can benefit from the work you’re putting in.

column2: The session began with the SI leader talking about the most recent exam. The students were immediately responsive and enthusiastic to talk about it. It seems that there is a good connection being made between the SI leader and the students that come to their sessions. The student knew exactly which questions they had and the SI leader went through the solutions asking questions and checking for understanding along the way.
column3: The students seemed actively engaged. The student felt that they were able to speak freely about both what they understood and what they struggled on. The SI leader then responded with questions or prompts to make them understand what they had done wrong instead of just giving them the answer. The speech was productive and there was no time wasted. The SI leader spoke kindly and let the student do most of the talking or leading of the conversation.
column4: The SI can improve on the presentation on certain questions or explanations. The students found themselves forgetting things that were previously briefly mentioned, but these weren’t written down. The explanations given could also be improved by having something written down while explaining so the students can have a visual along with the instructions.
column5: The SI leader provides their students with a lot of review materials outside of the classroom and session time. There we’re provided study guides for the exam as well as provided solutions to any questions or problems that were gone over during the session time.
column6: Overall the session went really well, the students seem really happy to attend and there seems to be a really nice community being created with this SI Leader. The only things I would think to improve upon is presentation of materials, ideas or questions. As the resources around you like whiteboards, paper or computers can be used to make sure the students can understand what you are saying, not just hear it.

column2: I think the opener, kwl chart, would have provided a great start for students to identify common struggles amongst their classmates and can also serve as an icebreaker for students(though only one student attended). The activities were also very helpful in that they provided extra practice problems for students to review old materials such as computing long divisions and performing checks using D * Q + R. I also liked the kahoot closer as it's always a more entertaining method to let students practice solving mcq questions in a short amount time, in which I find was a great way to help improve students' problem solving time on real exams.
column3: In one of the activity, where students were supposed to partner up with each other and take turns to solve a problem, Eddy was able to host this activity by acting as the partnering student when only one student showed up. Without giving direct hints or answers, Eddy asked guiding questions such as what concept are we supposed to apply when solving this type of problem and helped the student complete the problems very quickly. It also seemed that the student did not treat Eddy like a teacher and more like a real peer during that activity.
column4: The SI leader can try to make his activities more entertaining. The session environment felt very similar to a classroom where students just solve math problems and leaves. I think that in future sessions, the SI leader can include real world applications of the class materials or design problems in a game-style to motivate students to be more engaged.
column5: The SI leader was definitely very helpful in guiding students to master topics. The problems introduced in the session covered all class materials and were more difficult than practice questions from the lecture. The SI leader also checked for understanding by asking students to solve a similar problem with different values and explain their thought process from the start.
column6: Overall, the session offered a very productive and comfortable environment. The student reflected the effectiveness of the SI leader's activities through coming in not knowing how to solve many of the in-class problems to being able to handle higher level questions by themselves after the session. However, more different methods and marketing techniques can be implemented to make students feel more engaged to participate in the sessions such as marketing materials and more entertaining math activities.

column2: Overall, I think the session is great. SI leader had students go up to the whiteboard and do practice problems, and had the student walk him through the questions. Most of the time students were leading the SI leaders and explain his thought process.
column3: I like that the SI Leader used Thanksgiving as an opener, and how he acted just like another student in the class, solving problems together with the student.
column4: SI leader can work on incorporating more checking for understanding in the session.
column5: I like how SI leader have the student refer back to his note when he's struggling, instead of just giving off answers.
column6: Overall, I think you did a great job at fostering a comfortable learning. I also like you have student go to the whiteboard and handed him the markers to do the practice problem, which made the student more involved in the materials.

column2: The opener was really fun and collaborative. The main activities had great content and collaboration. And the closer was a nice, easy way to finish the session.
column3: SIL has a great connection with her students; they all get along and work well together most of the time. I think the students take advantage of that relationship to get off track, but Jasmin is pretty good at getting them back on track.
column4: Maybe use a little more wait time and redirect the question to other students. And make the Agenda a little more descriptive.
column5: She did a great job creating a fun, collaborative environment where all the students get along! Both main activities covered the topics that will help the students succeed on the quiz and exam content!
column6: Keep it up!🐐

column2: The opener was a check in google form, it went well I am not sure what was on it however I assume it had to do with possibly how a student feels about the course perhaps. Next was a brain dump activity on content that they went over in class. After that they went into practice problems that had to do with L'Hospitals Rule. Ending was higher or lower.
column3: Aditya, did a great job interacting with the student. The student seemed to be a regular, and had even said that he attended 13 sessions which is pretty good. They seemed to have a pretty good relationships occasionally making jokes while keeping the session on topic.
column4: I would say one thing you could improve on is wait time, it seemed that they were a little quick to answer some questions however, it is only one person so that may be a little more difficult which I understand.
column5: I would say the activities. The activities were short enough to go through them while connecting them together. And also being able to communicate well with the student and be able to have a fun and productive session.
column6: Great job! You seem to have the SI pillars down, and a great checking for understanding, as he could tell the student was strong on this part of the session, so decided to switch to material the student was weaker with to get more practice.

column2: The opener was spotle which was a great activity to keep the students engaged. The activities included having the students write what they know about the topic which was a great way to introduce the topic and have the students to start thinking on their own. I liked the matching activity because it allowed the students to collaborate on deciding which symbols relating to what definition and their units. I could appreciate that the session was planned on a slideshow so the activities flowed and the session was very efficient in getting practice, but also allowing the students to collaborate and have fun. The closer was a question posed to the students and i thought that was a good touch since it related to studying and some students could benefit from getting new ideas when studying.
column3: The SIL allowed the students to work together to find solutions, but also stepped in when necessary to guide them when they were confused. The SIL also encouraged the students and corrected them when they spoke negatively. The students were comfortable working in the session and interacted well with the SIL. The SIL also periodically did a temperature check of the room to see how the students were feeling about the topic.
column4: The SIL could share the answers with the students before moving on to the next question, that way the student can compare the real answer side by side to what they did so they'll be able to correct any mistakes made. This could also build their confidence. I would also say to have less wordy slides, or have the slides on the screen long enough for the students to not just read but to allow what they read to soak in before changing the slides.
column5: The SIL did a great job of guiding the students to figure the solution out themselves instead if just telling them the answer. The SIL did a great job making use of wait time and redirecting questions during the session to ensure all the students participated.
column6: Overall it was a good session and I enjoyed it. The content was relevant and you did a great job correcting the students without stepping in too much. I also liked that there were reminders at the end of the session, and the session ended on time.

column2: Jesse had an interesting opener that introduced the concept (indeterminate forms) in an interesting way.
column3: Jesse has a very welcoming environment for his students. In todays session, only one student came, but they talked about the other regulars that they usually see at his sessions. Along with that, they talked about shared experiences in the classroom, which implies that Jesse's relationship with them extends beyond the SI Session, which contributes to the unique interactions they have.
column4: Jesse is sometimes a little too quick when providing help. In the future he could probably use more wait time.
column5: Fostering a comfortable and welcoming environment for the students to participate in.
column6: Great atmosphere, could potentially push his students more by providing less help. Overall great session.

column2:
Opener: 
Opener was ok, student did not seem interested but SI instructor tried there best to get the student to work through binary operations which can have a good warming up affect before jumping into math content.

Activities:
Brain dump activity was good gave the student a way to remember and review what was done in class because they said they did not remember. SI instructor did a good job with good more in depth with content and getting the student to understand topic more deeply. Content practice was good to go through what the student did not know.

Closer:
Closer was a good wrap up with Wikipedia run.
column3: SI leader worked with well with a student who seemed disinterest but made the student feel safe to answers questions and speak there mind.
column4: SI leader did well with here activities but student did not have laptop or paper so maybe provided or projecting on the screen would help engage the student more rather then watch leader write on whiteboard.
column5: Keeping a disinterested student engaged in the session.
column6: Did very well, try and get more people if possible to cultivate a better environment and use projector if possible for students without any materials.

column2: I found the opener and closer activity more of an energy check than an activity involving collaboration to break ice between students as basic questions where asked like plans for break and finals. I like the activities the well-designed ,informative for the student learn outside the class
column3: No show. But as per the SI and I discussed ,the SI seems to guide students with easy examples and hints during learning activities
column4: The SI could have included the activities to have a part where the students can take a look back on the activities done in class so that they don't feel lost while solving the activities like they do as per the SI
column5: The course content activity on power point was really standard exam-like questions
column6: Nice session, really informative for the students to learn the course

column2: They go well together; the problems are very digestible, and its a nice idea to have a brain dump that is class-specific (sometimes makes them say more). Making their own formula sheets is a really fun closer idea!
column3: Not sure, no show, but we did discuss it briefly and everything seems as it should; they intend to ask them to check their notes, employ wait times, discuss study strategies, and simplify the question instead of giving a hint (which I find to be a cool idea).
column4: Try out a powerpoint instead of a document; looks nicer and there's more potential when presenting to students/sharing on the larger scale.
column5: The activities are super fun and varied (brain dump opener, formula cheat sheet closer), I love, unfortunate we didn't get to see them in action.
column6: Keep up the activities (especially the opener and closer!!) and test out powerpoints/slideshows! They don't work for everyone for sure but you never know aha
